          "title": "upload.test.ts exceeds 300-line limit (323 lines) \u2014 filesize gate fails",
          "body": "The file is 323 lines against a 300-line max. The gate fails. The three new show_branding tests (lines 223-323) are each fully self-contained and copy the same fetch-stub + spyOn boilerplate without sharing setup. Extracting a shared helper (e.g. a captureUpload() factory that sets up the mock and returns the captured FormData) would remove roughly 30-35 lines of duplication and bring the file under the limit. The existing happy-path test at line 102 already captures form data inline \u2014 a factory pattern here is consistent with how other test files in this repo use local helpers.",
          "confidence": "high"
        },
        {
          "file": "packages/rq-cli/src/commands/assets/upload.test.ts",
          "line": 123,
          "severity": "high",
          "category": "test-quality",
          "title": "upload.test.ts and update.test.ts not in test-quality allow-list for process spies \u2014 gate fails",
          "body": "The test-quality gate flags 25 instances of vi.spyOn(process.stdout/stderr/exit).mockImplementation() across upload.test.ts and update.test.ts. The allow-list in rq.config.json exempts output.test.ts, wire-command.test.ts, deal.test.ts, document.test.ts, market.test.ts, quote.test.ts, and tower.test.ts for exactly this pattern \u2014 but NOT upload.test.ts or update.test.ts. The spies are on OS I/O streams and process termination (external boundaries), so the pattern is legitimate. The fix is to add both files to the allow.test-quality list with the same reason string used by the existing exemptions: 'spies on process.stdout/stderr/exit \u2014 OS I/O streams and process termination are external boundaries, not internal code'.",
          "confidence": "high"
        },
        {
          "file": "packages/rq-cli/src/commands/assets/update.test.ts",
          "line": 258,
          "severity": "minor",
          "category": "correctness",
          "title": "--show-branding update test omits method and URL assertions required by plan",
          "body": "The plan (Task 3 Acceptance Criteria) states: 'Both tests assert the PATCH method and the URL match the existing happy-path shape.' The --no-show-branding test at line 219 correctly asserts captured.method === 'PATCH' and captured.url === the full URL. The --show-branding test at line 258 declares captured as { body?: unknown } only and never asserts method or URL. A future refactor that accidentally switches to a GET or changes the endpoint path would pass this test undetected. Fix: expand captured to include url and method, and add the same two assertions as the --no-show-branding test.",
          "confidence": "high"
        },
        {
          "file": "packages/rq-cli/src/commands/assets/update.test.ts",
          "line": 26,
          "severity": "important",
          "category": "correctness",
          "title": "afterEach missing vi.unstubAllGlobals() \u2014 fetch stub leaks between tests",
          "body": "The new tests at lines 219 and 258 both call vi.stubGlobal('fetch', mockFetch). The afterEach at lines 26-30 calls vi.restoreAllMocks() but NOT vi.unstubAllGlobals(). vi.restoreAllMocks() restores spies created with vi.spyOn() but does not restore globals set with vi.stubGlobal(). The fetch stub from a new test will persist into any subsequent test that does not also stub fetch \u2014 specifically, the existing tests (lines 110-217) that already existed in the file. upload.test.ts correctly has vi.unstubAllGlobals() in its afterEach (line 27). Fix: add vi.unstubAllGlobals() to the afterEach in update.test.ts.",
          "confidence": "high"
        }
      ]
    },
